span> Gerah</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">גֵּרָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(gerah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod30:13\">EXO 30:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev27:25\">LEV 27:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num3:47\">NUM 3:47</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num18:16\">NUM 18:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek45:12\">EZK 45:12</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">In all of these references, the <em>gerah</em> only appears as a definition of the shekel, of which it is 1/20; that is, the <em>gerah</em> has no significance apart from the shekel. If the name “shekel” is retained in translation, then the name “gerah” may also be kept. If the word “shekel” is translated, it may still be possible to retain the word “gerah,” because you will just be saying it is 1/20 of the unit used for “shekel.”</h2>\n</div>",
